  "local_port": 58276,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I add a floating chart (like freezing top row) in Excel 2013?",
  "response": "In Excel 2013, while there isn\u2019t a direct feature specifically for floating charts like the \"Freeze Panes\" option for rows and columns, you can achieve a similar effect by strategically placing your chart within frozen panes. This method ensures that your chart remains visible as you scroll through your data. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you set this up:\n\n### **Method: Embed the Chart in Frozen Panes**\n\n1. **Prepare Your Worksheet:**\n   - **Insert Your Data:** Organize your data in the worksheet as you normally would.\n   - **Position the Chart Area:** Decide where you want your chart to appear. It's best to place it at the top of the worksheet to utilize the freezing feature effectively.\n\n2. **Insert the Chart:**\n   - **Select Data for the Chart:** Highlight the data range you want to include in your chart.\n   - **Insert Chart:** Go to the **`Insert`** tab on the ribbon, choose your desired chart type (e.g., Column, Line, Pie), and insert it into the worksheet.\n   - **Position the Chart:** Drag the chart so that it resides within the top rows of your worksheet. Adjust the size as needed to fit within these rows.\n\n3. **Freeze the Top Rows (Including the Chart):**\n   - **Determine Rows to Freeze:** Identify how many top rows the chart occupies. For example, if your chart takes up the first 5 rows, you\u2019ll freeze these.\n   - **Select the Row Below:** Click on the row number immediately below your chart area. Using the previous example, you would select row **6**.\n   - **Freeze Panes:**\n     - Navigate to the **`View`** tab on the ribbon.\n     - Click on **`Freeze Panes`** in the **`Window`** group.\n     - From the dropdown, select **`Freeze Panes`** again.\n   \n   ![Freeze Panes Menu](https://i.imgur.com/OYJYBvR.png)\n\n   This action will freeze the top rows, ensuring that the chart remains visible as you scroll down through your data.\n\n4. **Adjust Chart Properties (Optional but Recommended):**\n   - **Lock the Chart Position:**\n     - Right-click on the chart and select **`Format Chart Area`**.\n     - In the **`Format Chart Area`** pane, go to **`Properties`**.\n     - Choose **`Don't move or size with cells`** to keep the chart fixed in place regardless of any changes to the worksheet below.\n   \n   ![Format Chart Properties](https://i.imgur.com/WlHv8eD.png)\n\n5. **Test the Setup:**\n   - **Scroll Through Data:** Scroll down your worksheet to ensure that the chart remains fixed in the frozen area.\n   - **Adjust as Needed:** If the chart doesn't remain visible, double-check the number of frozen rows and ensure the chart is entirely within those rows.\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n\n- **Sizing:** Ensure that the frozen rows are tall enough to fully display the chart without clipping.\n- **Multiple Charts:** If you wish to have multiple charts always visible, arrange them within the frozen pane area by adjusting row heights or using columns.\n- **Dynamic Charts:** For charts that need to update dynamically with data changes, ensure your data ranges are correctly set so that updates are reflected in the frozen chart.\n\n### **Alternative Method: Using a Separate Chart Sheet**\n\nIf embedding the chart within frozen panes doesn't meet your requirements, consider placing the chart on a separate sheet:\n\n1. **Create a New Chart Sheet:**\n   - Right-click on the current sheet tab and select **`Move or Copy`**.\n   - Choose **`(new book)`** and ensure **`Create a copy`** is checked if you want to keep the original data intact.\n   \n2. **Link Data:**\n   - Ensure that the new chart sheet references the main data sheet so that the chart updates automatically when data changes.\n\n3. **Arrange Windows:**\n   - Use the **`View`** tab to arrange both the data sheet and the chart sheet side by side for easier visibility.\n\nWhile this method doesn't \"float\" the chart within the same sheet, it allows you to view both the data and the chart concurrently.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nWhile Excel 2013 doesn't offer a dedicated floating chart feature, utilizing the \"Freeze Panes\" option effectively allows you to keep your chart visible as you navigate through your worksheet. This approach enhances readability and ensures that key visual data representations are always at hand.\n\n---\n\n**References:**\n- [Microsoft Office Support: Freeze Panes](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/freeze-panes-using-freeze-panes-options-021560c6-8a0a-4aab-9d81-4f77d0c5b16b)\n- [Microsoft Office Support: Create and move charts](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/create-a-chart-from-start-to-finish-e81f19d3-7eea-4c7c-82ba-d1a6abfa8692)",
